{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16648"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16648"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.04,0.04,0.35,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5069"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"},{"type":"tags","id":"9865"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDigoxin is a cardiac glycoside used to treat certain heart conditions. It works by inhibiting the sodium-potassium ATPase pump in cardiac myocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of sodium-potassium ATPase inhibition by digoxin on intracellular calcium and cardiac contractility?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases intracellular calcium and increases contractility","Decreases intracellular calcium and increases contractility","Increases intracellular calcium and decreases contractility","Decreases intracellular calcium and decreases contractility","Has no effect on intracellular calcium or contractility"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDigoxin \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreases intracellular calcium and increases contractility\u003C/strong\u003E through a cascade of events. Inhibition of the sodium-potassium ATPase pump leads to increased intracellular sodium. The elevated sodium reduces the concentration gradient that normally drives the sodium-calcium exchanger, resulting in reduced calcium efflux and increased intracellular calcium. This increases cardiac contractility. In this way digoxin acts as a positive inotrope, increasing cardiac contractility and therefore cardiac output. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism of action explains why the other options are incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Digoxin inhibits the sodium-potassium ATPase pump, leading to increased intracellular calcium and increased cardiac contractility.","The increased intracellular sodium from sodium-potassium ATPase inhibition reduces sodium-calcium exchanger activity, increasing intracellular calcium.","The positive inotropic effects of digoxin result from elevated intracellular calcium levels."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia"